=== WRITING RULES ===
- Write in plain, simple English. Short sentences. No jargon unless it appears in the document.
- No filler words or phrases. Do not use: "should be", "it is expected that", "the system will", "in order to", "please note", "make sure that", "as expected", "properly", "correctly", "successfully", "appropriate".
- Be specific and concrete in every field:
  - BAD step: "Enter valid data" → GOOD step: "Step 1: Type 'john.doe@company.com' in the Email field"
  - BAD result: "Login works correctly" → GOOD result: "Dashboard page loads showing 'Welcome, John' header"
  - BAD precondition: "User is set up" → GOOD precondition: "User account john.doe@company.com exists with active status"
- Each step = one physical user action. Name the exact UI element or API endpoint.
- Each expected result = one observable, verifiable outcome. State what appears, changes, or is returned.
- test_data must contain actual values, not placeholders like "valid email" or "test data".
- test_case names must describe the scenario AND the outcome: "test_case": "Login with expired password shows 'Your password has expired. Please reset it.' error and redirects to password reset page".

